        question: "Quelle est la préoccupation en matière de pertinence pour le membre de la famille études ?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "No concern—family members know what patients value", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Minor concern—family perspectives add context", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Moderate concern—family members report proxy views, not direct patient perspectives", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Serious concern—exclude family member studies entirely", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The question asks what PATIENTS value, not what others think patients value. Family perspectives are proxy data—valuable but not the direct perspective requested. Moderate concern is appropriate; the 4 studies contribute indirectly.",
          incorrect: "Family members may misunderstand or project their own values. If the question asks what patients value, studies of patient perspectives are directly relevant; proxy reports are only partially relevant."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "La déformation temporelle", title: "Directives 2023 tirées des données des années 1990",
        text: "A 2023 guideline on telehealth implementation cited a qualitative synthesis to support its recommendations on 'patient acceptance.' The synthesis seemed robust: <strong>18 studies</strong>, diverse settings, coherent findings.",
        followup: "But the studies dated from <strong>1995-2008</strong>—before smartphones, before widespread broadband, before video calling became routine. The synthesis described patients struggling with dial-up connections and fax machines. The COVID-19 pandemic had transformed telehealth acceptance, but the evidence base was <strong>two decades obsolete</strong>. Temporal relevance is relevance too."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
