  {
    id: 7, title: "Thematic Synthesis", subtitle: "Créer des thèmes à partir de données qualitatives", xp: 190,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "red-bg", content: { title: "Thematic Synthesis", subtitle: "Systematic approach to qualitative evidence synthesis" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand the three stages of thematic synthesis",
          "Distinguish descriptive from analytical themes",
          "Apply line-by-line coding to qualitative data",
          "Recognize common errors in thematic synthesis"
        ],
        tip: "La synthèse thématique comble le fossé entre l'examen narratif et la méta-analyse quantitative."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "L'histoire d'origine", title: "Thomas & Harden, 2008",
        text: "Dr. James Thomas et la Dre Angela Harden de l'EPPI-Centre ont été confrontés à un défi : comment synthétiser systématiquement des études qualitatives sur des questions de politique de santé. Les critiques narratives étaient trop subjectives. La méta-analyse ne correspondait pas aux données qualitatives.",
        followup: "They developed thematic synthesis—a method with <strong>three transparent stages</strong>: (1) line-by-line coding of primary study findings, (2) organizing codes into descriptive themes, and (3) generating analytical themes that answer the review question. Their 2008 paper has been cited over <strong>15,000 times</strong>. Thematic synthesis became the dominant method for qualitative synthesis in systematic reviews."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Les trois étapes",
        subtitle: "Des données à la compréhension",
        text: "<strong>Stage 1: Line-by-line coding</strong><br>Code every finding, quote, and author interpretation from primary studies. Stay close to original meaning.<br><br><strong>Stage 2: Descriptive themes</strong><br>Group related codes into broader themes that describe patterns across studies. Still grounded in the data.<br><br><strong>Stage 3: Analytical themes</strong><br>Generate higher-order themes that answer your review question. This is the interpretive leap—going beyond what studies explicitly say.",
        highlight: "Le passage des thèmes descriptifs aux thèmes analytiques est le moment où la synthèse ajoute de la valeur au-delà du résumé."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Le codage Catastrophe", title: "When Categories Came First",
        text: "Dr. Elena Volkov's team synthesized <strong>34 studies</strong> on patient experiences with diabetes apps. Before reading any data, they created <strong>12 predetermined codes</strong> based on behavior change theory: 'self-efficacy,' 'social support,' 'goal-setting,' and so on.",
        followup: "Every piece of data was forced into these boxes. Patients' frustrations with app design became 'low self-efficacy.' Concerns about data privacy became 'trust issues.' The synthesis confirmed the theory—because it was designed to. It missed the most important finding hidden in <strong>23 studies</strong>: patients felt infantilized by apps designed for newly-diagnosed users when they had decades of experience. The <strong>predetermined categories blinded them to the actual data</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📝", title: "Scenario: Coding Approach",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Vous entamez une synthèse thématique sur les freins au dépistage du cancer. Un collègue suggère de commencer par les catégories du modèle de croyance en matière de santé (susceptibilité perçue, gravité perçue, obstacles perçus, avantages perçus).",
        question: "Comment devez-vous réagir ?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Good idea—established frameworks ensure comprehensive coding", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Start with inductive line-by-line coding, then see if HBM concepts emerge", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Utilisez HBM pour la moitié des études, codage inductif pour la moitié", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Reject theoretical frameworks entirely in qualitative synthesis", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct ! La synthèse thématique nécessite d'abord un codage inductif : laisser les thèmes émerger des données plutôt que de forcer les données dans des catégories prédéterminées. Les cadres théoriques peuvent éclairer le développement ultérieur de thèmes analytiques, mais ne doivent pas limiter le codage initial.",
          incorrect: "Commencer avec des catégories prédéterminées risque de manquer ce que les données montrent réellement. Le codage inductif permet de faire émerger des découvertes inattendues. La théorie peut éclairer l'interprétation ultérieure, mais ne doit pas limiter la rencontre initiale avec les données."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Exemplary Synthesis", title: "L'étude sur le poids santé des enfants",
        text: "A thematic synthesis examined children's perspectives on healthy eating and physical activity. The team coded <strong>17 studies</strong> inductively, generating <strong>247 initial codes</strong>.",
        followup: "Codes were grouped into descriptive themes: 'taste preferences,' 'peer influence,' 'family food rules,' 'body image concerns.' But the analytical leap was crucial: these descriptive themes generated the finding that <strong>children experienced a fundamental tension between 'being healthy' and 'being normal'</strong>. This went beyond any single study—it was the synthesis insight. Guidelines could now address this tension directly, rather than just providing health information children already knew."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🎯", title: "Scenario: Descriptive vs Analytical",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Your descriptive themes from a synthesis on medication adherence include: 'forgetting doses,' 'side effect concerns,' 'cost barriers,' 'complex regimens,' and 'feeling better stopping early.' What analytical theme might unite these?",
        question: "Which represents an appropriate analytical theme?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "'Non-adherence has multiple causes'—summarizes the descriptive themes", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "'Patients weigh medication burden against perceived necessity'—interprets the pattern", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "'Healthcare providers should address adherence barriers'—recommends action", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "'Adherence interventions are needed'—identifies a gap", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The analytical theme identifies an underlying mechanism: patients conduct ongoing cost-benefit analysis of medications. This explains why forgetting, side effects, cost, complexity, and early stopping all matter—they're part of a coherent decision-making process. This insight can guide intervention design.",
          incorrect: "Un thème analytique doit interpréter le modèle, et pas seulement le résumer (A), recommander une action (C) ou identifier des lacunes (D). La valeur des thèmes analytiques explique POURQUOI les modèles descriptifs existent."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "L'échec de la transparence", title: "Thèmes venus de nulle part",
        text: "A highly-cited synthesis on 'patient empowerment' presented <strong>five elegant themes</strong>: knowledge acquisition, self-advocacy, partnership, emotional processing, and identity integration. The synthesis shaped hospital policies across three countries.",
        followup: "A replication attempt failed catastrophically. The team found no audit trail from codes to themes. The original authors couldn't explain how <strong>127 initial codes</strong> became exactly five themes. When pressed, they admitted the themes came from a framework paper by the senior author, published in 1998. The synthesis had reverse-engineered data to fit predetermined conclusions. <strong>Zero transparency</strong> meant zero credibility."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Thematic Synthesis Quality Markers",
        items: [
          "Line-by-line coding of primary data visible in supplementary materials",
          "Clear audit trail from codes to descriptive themes to analytical themes",
          "Multiple researchers involved in coding with disagreement resolution documented",
          "Analytical themes go beyond summarizing to generate new insight",
          "La non-confirmation des données reconnues et traitées"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "ENTREQ: Reporting Standards",
        subtitle: "Enhancing Transparency in Reporting Qualitative Research Synthesis",
        text: "The <strong>ENTREQ statement</strong> provides 21 items for transparent reporting of qualitative synthesis. Key items include:<br><br>• <strong>Search strategy:</strong> How studies were identified<br>• <strong>Study selection:</strong> Inclusion/exclusion criteria and process<br>• <strong>Quality appraisal:</strong> How methodological quality was assessed<br>• <strong>Data extraction:</strong> What data were extracted and by whom<br>• <strong>Synthesis methodology:</strong> Which method used and why",
        highlight: "ENTREQ aide les lecteurs à évaluer si votre synthèse peut être fiable et répliqué."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚠️", title: "Scénario : Passer à côté du point",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Une synthèse présente 8 thèmes descriptifs sur les expériences des patients souffrant de douleur chronique. Aucun thème analytique n’est fourni. La discussion indique : « Ces thèmes décrivent de manière exhaustive l'expérience du patient. »",
        question: "Qu'est-ce qui manque dans cette synthèse ?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Plus d'études pour atteindre la saturation", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Le travail d'interprétation qui génère des informations exploitables", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Analyse statistique du thème fréquence", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Rien – les thèmes descriptifs sont l'objectif", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "C'est exact ! Sans thèmes analytiques, la synthèse n’est qu’une description organisée. Le saut interprétatif – se demander « qu'est-ce que ce modèle signifie pour notre question de révision ? » - est ce qui rend la synthèse précieuse pour les politiques et la pratique. S'arrêter à la description ne répond pas à l'objectif de la méthode.",
          incorrect: "Thematic synthesis requires moving beyond description to analytical interpretation. Descriptive themes summarize; analytical themes explain and generate new understanding that individual studies couldn't provide."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Thematic Synthesis",
        items: [
          "Three stages: line-by-line coding → descriptive themes → analytical themes",
          "Commencez par un codage INDUCTIF : ne forcez pas les données dans des catégories prédéterminées",
          "Descriptive themes summarize; analytical themes INTERPRET",
          "The interpretive leap (Stage 3) is where synthesis adds value beyond summarizing",
          "Maintain transparent audit trail from codes to themes"
        ],
        remember: "Si vous vous arrêtez à la description, vous avez organisé mais pas synthétisé."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Best Practice", title: "L'abandon du tabac Synthèse",
        text: "A Cochrane qualitative synthesis on smoking cessation barriers took transparency seriously. They published their <strong>full coding framework</strong>, showing how 342 codes collapsed into 28 descriptive themes.",
        followup: "The audit trail was explicit: each analytical theme listed the descriptive themes it drew from, the codes within those themes, and the studies contributing to each code. Readers could trace any finding back to source data. The three analytical themes—<strong>'addiction as identity threat,' 'cessation as social navigation,' and 'healthcare encounters as missed opportunities'</strong>—each carried a complete evidence trail. This is how thematic synthesis builds credibility."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "What distinguishes analytical themes from descriptive themes?",
        options: [
          { text: "Analytical themes are more detailed than descriptive themes", correct: false },
          { text: "Analytical themes interpret patterns to generate new understanding", correct: true },
          { text: "Les thèmes analytiques sont validés par les auteurs de l'étude", correct: false },
          { text: "Analytical themes require more supporting studies", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Exactement. Les thèmes descriptifs organisent et résument les modèles de données dans les études. Les thèmes analytiques franchissent le pas de l'interprétation en expliquant ce que signifient ces modèles, pourquoi ils se produisent et ce qu'ils impliquent pour la question de révision. C’est là que la synthèse ajoute de la valeur au-delà de la collection.",
          incorrect: "La distinction n'est pas une question de détail ou de validation, mais une question d'interprétation. Les thèmes analytiques répondent à la question « et alors ? en générant une compréhension qui va au-delà de ce que les études individuelles ont explicitement déclaré."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 8, title: "Meta-Ethnography", subtitle: "Traduire les études les unes dans les autres", xp: 195,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "purple-bg", content: { title: "Meta-Ethnography", subtitle: "Noblit & Hare's approach to qualitative synthesis" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand the seven phases of meta-ethnography",
          "Distinguish reciprocal translation, refutational synthesis, and line of argument",
          "Apply translation concepts to real synthesis scenarios",
          "Recognize appropriate use cases for meta-ethnography"
        ],
        tip: "La méta-ethnographie traite chaque étude comme un texte à traduire, et non comme des données à agréger."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Le texte fondateur", title: "Noblit & Hare, 1988",
        text: "Sociologists George Noblit and Dwight Hare were frustrated. Educational research produced hundreds of qualitative studies that sat isolated, unable to accumulate into broader understanding. They asked: <strong>how do we synthesize interpretive research?</strong>",
        followup: "Their solution drew on translation theory. Rather than extracting 'data' from studies, they proposed <strong>translating studies into each other</strong>—preserving the interpretive nature of qualitative research while building cumulative understanding. Their 1988 book 'Meta-Ethnography' created an entirely new approach to synthesis, now widely used in health research."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Les Sept Phases",
        subtitle: "Noblit & Hare's framework",
        text: "<strong>1. Getting started:</strong> Identify your area of interest<br><strong>2. Deciding what is relevant:</strong> Define inclusion criteria<br><strong>3. Reading the studies:</strong> Repeated, deep engagement<br><strong>4. Determining how studies relate:</strong> Reciprocal, refutational, or line of argument<br><strong>5. Translating studies:</strong> Express concepts from one study in terms of another<br><strong>6. Synthesizing translations:</strong> Create overarching interpretation<br><strong>7. Expressing the synthesis:</strong> Communicate findings appropriately",
        highlight: "La phase 4 est le point de décision crucial : comment ces études sont-elles liées les unes aux autres ?"
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "The Lost in Translation", title: "47 études, Zero Synthesis",
        text: "Dr. Benjamin Okafor's team attempted a meta-ethnography of patient experiences with organ transplantation. They collected <strong>47 studies</strong> and dutifully extracted themes. Then they hit a wall.",
        followup: "Each study used different concepts: 'gift of life,' 'bodily integrity,' 'survivor guilt,' 'identity reconstruction,' 'medicalization.' The team couldn't see how to translate these into each other. After <strong>18 months</strong>, they published a thematic summary—but it wasn't a meta-ethnography. They had skipped the translation step that defines the method. The result was organized description, not synthetic interpretation."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔄", title: "Scenario: Reciprocal Translation",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "L'étude A révèle que les patients atteints de cancer subissent une « perturbation biographique ». L'étude B révèle que les patients atteints de cancer subissent une « transformation d'identité ». L'étude C révèle que les patients atteints de cancer subissent une « interruption du cours de leur vie ». Celles-ci semblent liées mais utilisent des termes différents.",
        question: "What type of synthesis relationship is this?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Réfutation : les études se contredisent", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Reciprocal translation—similar concepts with different terminology", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Line of argument—studies build a progression", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot determine—need more studies", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! These studies describe similar phenomena using different conceptual language. Reciprocal translation involves expressing one study's concepts in terms of another's—recognizing that 'biographical disruption,' 'identity transformation,' and 'life course interruption' may be different lenses on the same experience.",
          incorrect: "Ce ne sont pas des contradictions (réfutation) ou un argument de construction (argumentation). Ce sont des interprétations parallèles utilisant un vocabulaire différent. La traduction réciproque reconnaît cette similarité et crée une synthèse qui honore les nuances tout en identifiant le terrain d'entente."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Successful Translation", title: "La méta-ethnographie des maladies chroniques",
        text: "Dr. Frances Rapport's team synthesized <strong>38 studies</strong> on living with chronic fatigue syndrome. They identified key concepts from each study: 'loss of self,' 'invisible illness,' 'delegitimization,' 'illness identity,' 'biographical work.'",
        followup: "Through careful translation, they showed how 'loss of self' (one study) could be understood as related to 'biographical work' (another study)—both addressing the process of identity reconstruction. The synthesis produced a new conceptual model: <strong>'the self in chronic illness as continuously negotiated rather than lost.'</strong> This insight emerged from translation, not extraction."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Three Types of Synthesis",
        subtitle: "How studies relate determines approach",
        text: "<strong>Reciprocal Translation:</strong> Studies broadly agree. Translate concepts between them to develop a fuller understanding.<br><br><strong>Refutational Synthesis:</strong> Studies contradict. Explore and explain the contradictions rather than forcing agreement.<br><br><strong>Line of Argument:</strong> Studies address different aspects that together tell a larger story. Build an interpretive argument from the pieces.",
        highlight: "Most meta-ethnographies use reciprocal translation. Refutational synthesis is rare but valuable when genuine contradiction exists."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚔️", title: "Scenario: Refutational Synthesis",
        xp: 35,
        scenario: "Synthétiser les expériences des patients avec la télésanté : 5 études révèlent que les patients se sentent responsabilisés grâce à l'accès à distance. 4 études révèlent que les patients se sentent abandonnés par la perte de soins en personne. Ce ne sont pas des aspects différents : ce sont des expériences opposées.",
        question: "What synthesis approach is appropriate?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Reciprocal translation—find the common ground", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Argumentation : ce sont des étapes dans un processus", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Refutational synthesis—explore what explains the contradiction", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Exclude outlier studies to achieve coherence", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "C'est exact ! Ces études sont véritablement contradictoires. La synthèse réfutationnelle ne résout pas ce problème en forçant un accord : elle explore POURQUOI les patients ont des expériences opposées. Les différences de contexte, de population ou de mise en œuvre peuvent expliquer la réfutation. La synthèse s'enrichit en honorant la contradiction.",
          incorrect: "Don't force coherence where genuine disagreement exists. Refutational synthesis acknowledges and explores contradiction. The finding becomes: 'patient experience with telehealth is variable, depending on [factors that explain the contradiction].'"
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "L'argumentaire", title: "Building a Trajectory",
        text: "Dr. Khadija Mahmoud synthesized <strong>23 studies</strong> on refugee health service use. Individual studies focused on different moments: pre-migration health experiences, arrival challenges, navigation difficulties, long-term integration.",
        followup: "No single study covered the whole journey, but together they told a story. Using line of argument synthesis, she constructed a <strong>trajectory model</strong>: pre-migration health capital → arrival-related disruption → system navigation as skilled work → eventual (partial) integration. Each study contributed a piece; the synthesis built the whole. This is line of argument at its best—<strong>the whole exceeds the sum of parts</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🧭", title: "Scenario: Identifying Synthesis Type",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Vous synthétisez des études qualitatives sur l'épuisement professionnel des travailleurs de la santé. L'étude A porte sur le stress en début de carrière. L’étude B porte sur la désillusion à mi-carrière. L'étude C couvre les stratégies d'adaptation en fin de carrière. L'étude D couvre les facteurs organisationnels à toutes les étapes de carrière.",
        question: "What synthesis approach fits best?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Reciprocal translation—all about burnout", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Refutational synthesis—different career stages contradict", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Line of argument—build a career trajectory model of burnout", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Separate syntheses for each career stage", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Studies A, B, and C address different aspects of a phenomenon that unfolds over time. Line of argument synthesis can build a developmental model of burnout across career stages, with Study D providing cross-cutting organizational context. The synthesis creates understanding none could provide alone.",
          incorrect: "Ceux-ci ne sont pas contradictoires (réfutations) ou ne disent pas la même chose différemment (réciproque). Ce sont des éléments d’un tableau plus vaste. La synthèse d'une ligne d'argumentation construit un tout à partir de parties complémentaires."
        }
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Meta-Ethnography Quality Indicators",
        items: [
          "Études lues plusieurs fois avec un engagement profond",
          "Concepts/métaphores clés extraits de chaque étude",
          "Raisonnement explicite sur les relations d'étude (réciproque/réfutation/ligne de argument)",
          "Processus de traduction décrit : comment les concepts de différentes études étaient liés",
          "Synthesis goes beyond description to produce new interpretation",
          "Original study interpretations preserved while building higher-order understanding"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Alternative: JBI Methodology",
        subtitle: "Joanna Briggs Institute approach to qualitative synthesis",
        text: "The <strong>JBI (Joanna Briggs Institute)</strong> offers an alternative systematic approach:<br><br>• <strong>Meta-aggregation:</strong> Preserves original meanings by aggregating findings rather than re-interpreting<br>• <strong>ConQual:</strong> JBI's approach to assessing confidence (similar to CERQual)<br>• <strong>SUMARI software:</strong> Dedicated tool for JBI systematic reviews<br><br>JBI is particularly popular in nursing and allied health research.",
        highlight: "Choose your method based on purpose: meta-ethnography for theory-building, thematic synthesis for policy, JBI meta-aggregation for preserving original meanings."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Meta-Ethnography Excellence", title: "The Campbell Collaboration Review",
        text: "A Campbell Collaboration review used meta-ethnography to synthesize <strong>51 studies</strong> on community responses to environmental disasters. The team published their translation table showing exactly how they connected concepts across studies.",
        followup: "The table showed: 'collective efficacy' (Study 3) was translated as relating to 'community resilience' (Study 7) and 'social capital mobilization' (Study 12). Different terms, related concepts. The final synthesis produced a model of <strong>'community coherence'</strong>—a new concept that captured what individual studies approached from different angles. This is the power of meta-ethnography: creating conceptual vocabulary that transcends any single study."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "✅", title: "Scénario : sélection de méthode",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Vous devez synthétiser 15 études qualitatives pour une directive clinique. Les études utilisent des méthodes diverses (entretiens, groupes de discussion, ethnographie) et des cadres conceptuels quelque peu différents. Vous avez besoin de résultats exploitables pour vous entraîner.",
        question: "La méta-ethnographie est-elle la meilleure approche ?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Yes—meta-ethnography works for all qualitative synthesis", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "No—thematic synthesis is more appropriate for guideline-focused reviews", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Yes—diverse methods require sophisticated synthesis", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Neither—use framework synthesis instead", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Meta-ethnography excels at conceptual development and theory-building but may be less suitable for applied guideline questions requiring actionable findings. Thematic synthesis was designed specifically for policy/practice questions, producing findings more readily translated into recommendations.",
          incorrect: "Le choix de la méthode doit correspondre à l'objectif. La méta-ethnographie donne la priorité à la traduction conceptuelle et au développement théorique. Pour les directives cliniques nécessitant des résultats pratiques, la synthèse thématique fournit souvent des résultats plus directement exploitables."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Meta-Ethnography",
        items: [
